item.content:encoded:
There's a gap between what you ask Claude Code to do and what it actually does — and most of the time, that gap is fine. But sometimes, you need a guarantee, not a suggestion. "Don't touch " is easy to write in . It's harder to enforce.\
Hooks are Claude Code's answer to that problem. They let you intercept its lifecycle at specific points and inject deterministic behavior: run a linter, block a command, send a notification, or reject a prompt. The difference from the instructions in  is that hooks don't depend on Claude reading and remembering them — they fire unconditionally, every time, regardless of context window state.\
This article covers the hook system: what events exist, how configuration works, which hook types to reach for, and where the realistic limits are. I'll also walk through two patterns I've found worth the setup cost.A hook is a handler you attach to a named lifecycle event. When that event fires, Claude Code passes JSON context to your handler via stdin (for command hooks) or as an HTTP POST body (for HTTP hooks). Your handler inspects the input, optionally emits a decision, and Claude Code acts on it.\
The keyword is . A prompt instruction can be ignored, compressed out of context, or misunderstood. A hook that exits with code 2 blocks the tool call — full stop. This also means hooks are immune to the context window pressure covered in the previous article: they fire from configuration, not from what Claude currently holds in memory.\
Hook configuration lives in , under the  key:{
  "hooks": {
    "PreToolUse": [
      {
        "matcher": "Bash",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": ".claude/hooks/check-command.sh"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
The structure is: event name → array of matcher groups → each group has a matcher and an array of handlers. The matcher filters which tool calls activate the group. If you omit it or use , the group fires on every occurrence of the event.There are around 20 lifecycle events. Most of them you'll never need. The ones worth knowing:Inside the agentic loop (fire repeatedly): — fires before a tool call executes. Can block it. This is the main enforcement point. — fires after a tool call succeeds. Use it for formatting, logging, and side effects. — fires after a tool call fails. Useful for cleanup or alerting. — fires when you submit a prompt, before Claude processes it. Can inject context or reject the prompt. — fires when a permission dialog appears. Let’s you auto-approve or deny programmatically. — fires when Claude finishes a response. Good for running tests or triggering post-completion work.\
Session-level (fire once or on specific conditions): — fires when a session begins or resumes. Use it to inject the environment context. — fires when the session terminates. For cleanup or audit logging. — fires when a  or  file is loaded into the context. Observe only — no decision control. — fires when a config file changes during a session. For audit logging.\
The rest — , , , , , and others — matter once you're deep into multi-agent workflows, which I'll cover in a later article. Worth flagging separately:  and  fire around Claude Code's automatic context compaction. If you've read the previous article on the context window tax, these events make immediate sense —  lets you inject a summary before the compaction runs, which can influence what gets preserved.Four handler types exist. They cover different cost/capability tradeoffs: () — runs a shell script. The simplest and most common. Gets JSON on stdin, returns decisions via exit code and stdout. Use this for anything that fits in a bash script or calls a local binary.\
 () — POSTs the event JSON to a URL and reads the response. Good for centralized logging or integrating with external services, but adds latency on every matched event. This is also relevant for MCP server workflows — the next article covers MCP servers in detail, but the short version is that  and  hooks can intercept MCP tool calls by name, so you can apply the same enforcement patterns to tools coming from an external server as you would to Claude's built-in tools.\
 () — sends the event to a Claude model for a yes/no evaluation. Useful when the decision requires semantic judgment — "does this command look like it's cleaning up temp files or something else?" — that a regex can't reliably make. Slower and token-consuming, so use it selectively.\
 () — spawns a subagent with access to tools like Read, Grep, and Glob. For decisions that require inspecting the codebase before allowing a tool call. The most powerful type, also the most expensive.\
For most real-world hooks, command type is the right default. The others are for cases where a shell script genuinely can't make the call.For command hooks, the exit code is how you communicate intent back to Claude Code: — success. Claude Code parses stdout for any JSON decision output and proceeds. — blocking error. Claude Code ignores stdout. The stderr text is fed back to Claude as an error message. For , this blocks the tool call. For , it rejects the prompt. The exact behavior is event-specific. — non-blocking error. The hook failed, but Claude Code continues.\
A  hook that wants to block a command outputs a JSON decision:#!/bin/bash
# .claude/hooks/block-env-writes.sh
INPUT=$(cat)
TOOL=$(echo "$INPUT" | jq -r '.tool_name')
FILE=$(echo "$INPUT" | jq -r '.tool_input.path // empty')

if [[ "$TOOL" == "Write" && "$FILE" == *".env"* ]]; then
  echo "Blocked: .env files must not be modified by Claude Code" >&2
  exit 2
fi

exit 0
\
And the hook configuration to wire it up:{
  "hooks": {
    "PreToolUse": [
      {
        "matcher": "Write",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/.claude/hooks/block-env-writes.sh"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
\
Note the  prefix. Hook paths in  are resolved relative to the working directory at the time Claude Code runs — which can vary. Using the environment variable ensures the path resolves correctly regardless of where you launch the session.Two Patterns Worth the Setup CostMost hook ideas sound useful until you think about the maintenance overhead. A hook that runs on every  event and does something slow will make every tool call feel sluggish. A hook that sends exit 2 on ambiguous conditions will interrupt Claude constantly. I've settled on two patterns that earn their keep: with a  matcher — run your formatter after every file write, silently in the background. No more "please run prettier on this" in every session.#!/bin/bash
# .claude/hooks/format-on-write.sh
INPUT=$(cat)
FILE=$(echo "$INPUT" | jq -r '.tool_input.path // empty')

if [[ -z "$FILE" ]]; then
  exit 0
fi

EXT="${FILE##*.}"

case "$EXT" in
  ts|tsx|js|jsx)
    npx prettier --write "$FILE" 2>/dev/null
    ;;
  py)
    ruff format "$FILE" 2>/dev/null
    ;;
esac

exit 0
\
Make it async so it doesn't block the next tool call:{
  "hooks": {
    "PostToolUse": [
      {
        "matcher": "Write",
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/.claude/hooks/format-on-write.sh",
            "runInBackground": true
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
\
One caveat worth knowing before you deploy this: formatter output fed back into the session adds to your context. If your session involves many small file edits and a slow formatter, repeated formatting passes can consume a surprisingly large portion of the context window. The previous article goes into what actually burns tokens in a session — if you find formatting hooks making long sessions degrade faster than expected, that's where to look.Notification when Claude goes idleThe  event fires when Claude Code sends a notification — including when it's waiting for permission or has finished a long task. I run a script that triggers a system notification. After spending ten minutes doing something else while Claude works, I'd rather not have to check whether it's done.#!/bin/bash
# .claude/hooks/notify.sh
INPUT=$(cat)
MESSAGE=$(echo "$INPUT" | jq -r '.message // "Claude Code needs attention"')

# macOS
osascript -e "display notification \"$MESSAGE\" with title \"Claude Code\""

exit 0
{
  "hooks": {
    "Notification": [
      {
        "hooks": [
          {
            "type": "command",
            "command": "$CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/.claude/hooks/notify.sh",
            "runInBackground": true
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
Hooks that fire too broadlyA hook without a matcher — or with a  matcher — fires on every occurrence of the event. If you attach something expensive to  with no matcher, it runs before every single tool call in the session. Read, Grep, Glob, Write, Bash — all of them. Use matchers to narrow the scope.\
The  field inside a handler provides a second filter layer:{
  "type": "command",
  "if": "Bash(rm *)",
  "command": ".claude/hooks/check-rm.sh"
}
\
The  check is evaluated before the handler spawns. If it doesn't match, no process is created. Use it to avoid the overhead of running a script for tool calls that clearly don't need it.The event JSON arrives on stdin — not as arguments, not as environment variables. The single environment variable that Claude Code sets is , which indicates whether the session is running headlessly. That's it. If your script tries to read input any other way, it gets nothing, makes a wrong decision, and you'll spend time wondering why the hook isn't working.# Wrong
FILE=$1

# Right
INPUT=$(cat)
FILE=$(echo "$INPUT" | jq -r '.tool_input.path // empty')
Using hooks as a replacement for  permissionsHooks run your code. They're not a policy system — they're automation. If the goal is to prevent Claude from accessing a file, a  rule in  (however imperfect) plus a  hook gives you defense in depth. A hook alone is not the right tool for a pure access-control problem, because hook scripts can themselves have bugs.Use the  command inside a Claude Code session to browse and toggle configured hooks without editing JSON directly.Run Claude Code with  (verbose mode) to see hook stdout in the terminal — useful for debugging.Place hook scripts in  and reference them with $CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR/.claude/hooks/your-script.sh. Commit them to the repo so they're available to everyone on the team.Keep hook scripts focused. A script that does three things is harder to debug than three scripts that do one thing each.Hooks give you deterministic control over Claude Code's lifecycle — something that  instructions alone can't provide. The surface is larger than it looks (around 20 events, four handler types), but in practice, most useful setups touch two or three events with command-type handlers.\
The two patterns I'd start with: auto-format on write with , and a  hook so you stop babysitting long sessions. Add  guards for any files that must never be modified. Everything else can wait until you hit a specific problem.\
In the next article, I'll look at MCP servers — which ones are actually worth adding, what the setup friction looks like in practice, and a few I've removed after trying them.

Part 2 of 2. Part 1 covers building the service from scratch — including when you have no access to the systems you're integrating with.The service had been in production for a couple of months. Time to find out what it actually looked like under load.Not a synthetic benchmark — a realistic test using actual API calls, real request parameters sourced from public business registries, and the full processing pipeline end to end. The goal: understand the behavior at scale, find the bottlenecks, and fix what needs fixing.The results were not what I expected. Our system wasn't the problem.💡 LLM Tip: Generate the tooling, not just the testsI needed a Python script with configurable batch submission, parallel async polling, timing collection (submission latency, end-to-end processing time), parameter verification, and a structured report with status breakdowns and p95 latencies.I also needed realistic test data — actual company and sole proprietor identifiers guaranteed to return results. These were sitting in reference documents in various formats.Both the test framework and the data extraction were done in 2 hours with Claude. Without LLM assistance: a full day of setup before any testing could begin. The data parsing alone — extracting structured records from multi-format government reference documents — would have been tedious work.In about 3 minutes, with only minor delays, 100,000 requests were sent. The only synchronous part of the project—the API—worked without any issues.| Metric | Value |
|----|----|
| CPU (all job containers, peak) | 0.047 cores |
| Memory (peak per container) | ~128 MB |
| Lock contention on the message queue | None observed |
| Requests completed within 1 hour | ~6000 |
| Requests waiting on the external system | ~94,000 |
| Job replicas during test | 2 |
| Internal messages per request | ~10–15 |
| Peak queue depth | ~150k messages |CPU at 0.047 cores — five hundredths of a core. The workers were not compute-bound.The external system was the bottleneck. Just 6% requests were completed in the first hour. The rest were waiting on responses from the external infrastructure — some arriving hours later, some from a previous test run still pending days later.Our queue was empty. We were just waiting. This is expected behavior for a system with a five-working-day SLA, but worth confirming empirically. The test answered the question: our processing capacity is not the constraint.When responses did start arriving in bulk — thousands within a short window — a different picture emerged.Where Things Actually Got SlowThe Real Bottleneck: Worker CountEach request generates approximately 10-15 internal messages across its full lifecycle: state transitions, document processing, result dispatch, and audit events. So, 100,000 requests = up to 1,500,000 internal messages.With 2 job replicas, each processing one message at a time, the queue depth grew faster than it could be consumed when bulk responses arrived.Adding replicas produced near-linear throughput improvement:2 replicas  → baseline throughput
4 replicas  → ~2x throughput  
8 replicas  → ~4x throughput
Linear scaling is the result you want — it means the bottleneck is parallelism, not shared state or resource contention. The Doctrine transport's locking held up. The database was not the constraint.Next step: Kubernetes HPA configured to scale on queue depth, so replica count adjusts automatically.The timeout retry service scans pending requests periodically, re-queues those waiting too long, and marks requests as failed after exceeding retry limits. Query pattern:SELECT * FROM requests
WHERE status_code = 'timeout'
ORDER BY created_at;
Separate indexes on  and  — but no composite index (just forgot it because of the hurry up). Under load with thousands of pending requests, PostgreSQL wasn't using both. One fix:CREATE INDEX idx_requests_status_created
ON requests (status_code, created_at);
Rule: if you have a WHERE clause and an ORDER BY that always appear together, they probably belong in one composite index. Obvious in retrospect.Problems Fixed Before the Load TestA few issues found during development — documented here because they're instructive.When a response includes file references, the service needs all referenced documents processed before marking the request complete. Initial implementation:if ($request->getQuantityFiles() !== $processedFiles) {
    sleep(10);
    return new AsyncRequestMessage(requestId: $request->getId());
}
Worker blocked for 10 seconds doing nothing. Under load with many file-heavy requests, workers pile up, sleeping, starving other messages.The fix: re-dispatch with a delay stamp, releasing the worker immediately.if ($request->getQuantityFiles() !== $processedFiles) {
    return new Envelope(
        new AsyncRequestMessage(requestId: $request->getId()),
        [new DelayStamp(10000), new RetryCountStamp(attempts: $attempts + 1)]
    );
}
The worker returns immediately. Message reappears after 10 seconds. The worker handles other messages in the meantime. Functionally identical behavior, completely different resource profile under load.The DispatchAfterCurrentBusStamp TrapWe used DispatchAfterCurrentBusStamp on the first dispatched message — intent: ensure the controller returns its HTTP response before processing begins.This stamp is designed for use within message handlers, where it defers dispatch until after the current handler completes. From an HTTP controller, the behavior is different: if a worker picks up the message before the HTTP response is flushed, the controller can block. We saw this intermittently under load — the endpoint hung while a worker was processing the newly dispatched message.Fix: a small initial delay instead.$this->messageBus->dispatch(
    new AsyncRequestMessage(requestId: $requestId),
    [new DelayStamp(1000)]
);
Controller returns UUID. Message available 1 second later. No race possible.Lesson: understand what Symfony stamps actually do before reaching for them. The documentation describes the intent; the behavior under specific conditions requires testing.Streaming Document DeliveryDocuments from external file storage are streamed — read in chunks, written directly to the response, never buffered in full. The external storage API was idiosyncratic: inconsistent  headers, occasional mid-stream errors, responses compressed as ZIP archives requiring on-the-fly extraction."Stream it" is not a complete implementation. A mid-stream failure, leaving a client with a partial response, is worse than a clean error. Graceful handling of connection drops, proper error propagation through the stream chain, and cleanup on partial delivery required explicit attention at every boundary.Cleaning Doctrine after handling between messages — long-running workers accumulate entities in Doctrine's Identity Map; explicit clearing prevents memory growth.The service works well. It also has rough edges we've accepted.The external system occasionally returns schema-invalid XML. We handle it — log it, mark the request for manual inspection — but we don't fully understand the pattern. Some edge cases in XAdES validation we still don't fully trust; our test coverage for malformed signature scenarios is thinner than I'd like. And a small percentage of requests with complex file structures still require occasional manual intervention when the document storage returns unexpected responses.These aren't blockers. But they're real, and pretending otherwise would be dishonest.The service is in production. Immediate roadmap:Kubernetes HPA on queue depth — we confirmed linear scaling works, now automate it with KEDAPer-step timing instrumentation — we know the external system is the ceiling, but we don't have granular data on internal step latency. Profiling will tell us if XML generation or signing steps have optimization potentialRabbitMQ/Redis transport evaluation — not because PostgreSQL is failing, but to understand the tradeoff empirically before we need itMost integration architecture isn't about elegance.It's about building reliable software around systems you can't access, can't fully trust, and can't control — and surviving long enough for the real system to finally reveal itself.The load test confirmed what the architecture was designed to handle: our processing is correct and scales linearly. The ceiling is external, not internal. That's where you want it.Building something similar? I'd be happy to discuss specifics in the comments.

:::info
A zero-shot experiment: one prompt, five known-vulnerable contracts from the SmartBugs Curated benchmark, and an unexpected pattern in how an LLM judges severity.Model: Claude Sonnet 4.6 · Claude ProProtocol: Zero-shot · fresh context per contractBenchmark: SmartBugs Curated (ICSE 2020)Claude Sonnet 4.6 found a security bug in each of the five contracts I tested — all of them — without providing a hint, example or setting up anything special. In addition, it placed every single finding at the highest level of risk —  — whether the bug was truly critical or not. This combination of great detection ability versus overconfidence in rating is the practical use of this test.WHY SMART CONTRACT SECURITY IS CATEGORICALLY DIFFERENTA Smart Contract is a program running on top of the Ethereum Blockchain. It can never be fixed once it has been implemented. It is public, permanent, and will run until it runs out of money. A security bug is not something that needs to be managed — it is an open-door sign for hackers, which will stay open forever if the contract has money in it.The  demonstrated this perfectly: a hacker exploited a re-entrancy flaw in the contract and stole 3.6 million ETH in a single transaction. All the community could do was perform a hard fork — rewrite the whole history of the blockchain. Just two years later, a simple math error in BECToken resulted in hundreds of millions lost due to a simple mathematical calculation. Those were not new or sophisticated attacks. They have been around for a while, yet they continue to appear in live production contracts today.Manually auditing experts are the solution to this problem; manually auditing experts can cost from 50 thousand to 200 thousand USD and take weeks. Static analysis tools like  (which includes a library of rules) and symbolic execution tools like  are cheap and quick; they only identify deviations from known patterns. They don't know how a function should work and therefore can't determine whether the implementation provides safety based on what the author said the implementation would provide.Large Language Models, though, represent a completely different way of thinking: LLMs are trained on both source code and audit reports/post-mortem analyses and therefore ask the same questions that a human auditor would — did the developer implement their code as stated, and does the implementation ensure safety?I utilized the  — a collection of research-proven, verified Solidity smart contracts that contain exactly annotated vulnerabilities at the line level (as introduced at ICSE 2020). Five such smart contracts were used, each representing a different type of vulnerability. Each smart contract was submitted into a new conversation with no previous interactions or "hint" information. Additionally, the same structured prompt was used for each contract:# Identical prompt — five fresh conversations
You are a senior smart contract security auditor.
Analyze the following Solidity contract and identify ALL vulnerabilities.
For EACH finding provide:
  1. Vulnerability Name   2. SWC ID
  3. Exact line number(s) 4. Severity: Critical / High / Medium / Low
  5. Plain-English explanation of the risk
  6. Suggested fix in Solidity
--- CONTRACT CODE BELOW ---
\
Stylistically requiring  IDs and specific line numbers for Claude is essential to forcing it to produce specific, verifiable statements about the vulnerability(s) present in the benchmark.THE FIVE VULNERABILITY CLASSES TESTEDThis contract withdraws funds from an account without first clearing the account's balance. Therefore, an attacker can deploy a contract containing a fallback function that immediately calls  after deploying the contract. Because the account's balance has not been cleared, the withdrawal will succeed over and over again until the account is depleted.// reentrancy_simple.sol — GT: SWC-107 at line 24
pragma solidity ^0.4.15;
contract Reentrance {
  mapping(address => uint) userBalance;
  function withdrawBalance() public {
    // external call BEFORE state update — vulnerable
    if(!(msg.sender.call.value(userBalance[msg.sender])())) { throw; }
    userBalance[msg.sender] = 0;  // too late
  }
}
The appropriate sequence of operations to avoid this type of reentrancy attack is known as Checks-Effects-Interactions (CEI): let CC, EE, II represent the check, state update, and interaction phases of a transaction. CEI ensures that safe transactions are executed in strict sequential order:C(f)≺E(f)≺I(f)C()≺E()≺I()CEI INVARIANT — PLACING II BEFORE EE OPENS A RE-ENTRY WINDOWClaude correctly identified lines 22–25 as Critical and generated a complete working  contract with a fallback loop demonstrating the exploitation of the attack at each step. This type of demonstration typically occurs in formal audits and would have cost money.2 · Integer Underflow (SWC-101)Prior to version 0.8 of Solidity, all arithmetic is performed automatically in modulus 22562256. Thus, when a programmer performs an unchecked subtraction:uint public count = 1;
function run(uint256 input) public {
  count -= input;  // no bounds check — underflows silently
}count−input≡1−2≡2256−1(mod2256)count−input≡1−2≡2256−1(mod2256)RESULT: 115,792,089,237,316,...,639,935 — THE MAXIMUM UINT256 VALUE, FROM ONE SUBTRACTION
Claude correctly stated exactly which line represented the issue, the correct SWC ID, and also determined the wrap-around value — although this might look similar to some form of mathematical reasoning, it may just be rote memorization since the benchmarks are publicly available. With versions of Solidity >= 0.8, this operation will revert automatically; otherwise, it is a silent trap.3 · tx.origin Auth Bypass (SWC-115)In a call chain A→B→C→→, Ethereum ensures that  (the original authorizer of a transaction) and  (the current call's sender). Therefore, in a conditional statement that utilizes require(tx.origin == owner), it would pass for any transaction initiated by the owner — regardless of whether a malicious contract Bsits in the middle of the call chain. To fix this issue use require(msg.sender == owner).4 · Timestamp Manipulation (SWC-116)Block Producers have very little discretion over . For the condition , a validator simply submits the proposed block at that point in time; therefore, the win probability becomes 1.0 rather than 1/15. Anybody who has access to an Atomic Helper Contract can take advantage of this same condition in order to benefit themselves. The best method to handle this is by using a verifiable, on-blockchain Random Number Generator such as .5 · Unchecked Send (SWC-104)Solidity's  method will return  upon failure — ignoring that return value allows the rest of the execution to occur, allowing state flags such as to remain set even though the transfer itself never occurred — leaving the funds locked forever with no recovery path available.The classification pipeline formalises how each finding was scored against the ground truth:ALGORITHM 1 — ZERO-SHOT LLM AUDIT EVALUATIONInput:&nbsp; C&nbsp;= {c₁ … c₅} contracts,&nbsp;&nbsp;L&nbsp;= ground-truth SWC labels,&nbsp;&nbsp;P&nbsp;= audit promptOutput:&nbsp;T&nbsp;= per-contract classification {CAUGHT, MISSED} \n for each&nbsp;cᵢ&nbsp;in&nbsp;C:open fresh isolated conversation on claude.airᵢ&nbsp;← Claude(&nbsp;P&nbsp;+ source(cᵢ) )// zero-shot, no prior contextFᵢ&nbsp;← parse(rᵢ)&nbsp;// extract SWC-ID, line, severity per findingDᵢ&nbsp;← { f ∈ Fᵢ : SWC(f) ∈ L[cᵢ]&nbsp;&nbsp;and&nbsp;|line(f) − GT_line| ≤ 2 }Bᵢ&nbsp;← { f ∈ Fᵢ : f ∉ L[cᵢ]&nbsp;&nbsp;and&nbsp;validRisk(f) }&nbsp;// bonus findingsT[cᵢ] ←&nbsp;CAUGHT&nbsp;if&nbsp;Dᵢ ≠ ∅&nbsp;else&nbsp;MISSEDrecord |Dᵢ|, |Bᵢ|, severity comparisonreturn&nbsp;TA finding was scored  if Claude correctly identified the vulnerable SWC ID number and was able to identify the exact location of the vulnerable statement within ±2 lines. This allowed for some wiggle room for potential header comment line numbers found in Claude's numbered source files.5/5PRIMARY VULNERABILITIES CAUGHT22TOTAL FINDINGS ACROSS 5 CONTRACTS0REJECTED IN MANUAL REVIEW| CONTRACT | CAUGHT? | CLAUDE SEVERITY | BENCHMARK | BONUS |
|----|----|----|----|----|
| reentrancysimple | ✔ | Critical | Critical | 4 |
| intoverflow_min | ✔ | Critical | High | 2 |
| phishable | ✔ | Critical | High | 3 |
| roulette | ✔ | Critical | High | 4 |
| lotto | ✔ | Critical | High | 4 |
| Total | 5 / 5 | All Critical | — | 17 | Primary (green) and bonus (orange) findings per contract. Claude surfaced additional valid findings in every contract — 22 total from a single structured prompt; zero rejected in author manual review.THE SEVERITY PATTERN — WRONG DIRECTION, RIGHT INSTINCTThe SmartBugs benchmark assigns  to reentrancy (SWC-107) and  to the other four classes. Claude assigned Critical to all five. Two observations:First, if we assume that there are no  blocks or inline assembly statements in the given Solidity >= 0.8 codebase, then any ordinary SWC-101 findings should be reduced in severity because automatic revert protection is built into the compiler. Therefore, run-time underflow is virtually impossible. However, Claude doesn't check the pragma version prior to determining which level of severity to assign.Second, for a security tool, what really matters is whether you incorrectly move your error up or down — not just in terms of magnitude, but also in terms of direction. An incorrect increase from High to Critical means that an additional hour of review time was wasted. On the other hand, an incorrect decrease from Critical to Medium may mean that a draining vulnerability was sent out into production without being reviewed. Claude correctly erred on the side of caution.5/5&nbsp;detection&nbsp;rate⇒95%&nbsp;Wilson&nbsp;CI=[47.8%,&nbsp;100%]5/5&nbsp;detection&nbsp;rate⇒95%&nbsp;Wilson&nbsp;CI=[47.8%,&nbsp;100%]WIDE INTERVAL — ONE MISSED DETECTION WOULD DROP THE ESTIMATE TO 80%. READ AS A PROMISING SIGNAL, NOT A PERFORMANCE SPECIFICATION.The five contracts are from publicly available repositories that have been online since 2018, have been referenced and used in multiple academic research articles, blogs, and in security training materials. It is almost certain that Claude was exposed to these same five vulnerability patterns prior to training. While this doesn't render the experiment irrelevant, it modifies the statement made by the results: the study has demonstrated Claude's ability to identify five commonly documented vulnerability patterns reliably within the context of this small test. However, whether or not this demonstrates Claude can identify additional, privately developed, post-training contracts remains to be tested.01 — USE STRUCTURED QUESTIONS.Requiring SWC ID and specific lines of code will allow Claude to provide answers that are both falsifiable and verifiable. Using a Role–Task–Format structure here (auditor role, exactly six fields per finding, explicitly classify using SWC), allows for direct comparison of Claude's responses to standard format audit reports issued by auditors in the contracting business.02 — ADJUST SEVERITY BASED ON COMPILER VERSION.Wherever there is a Solidity >= 0.8 version of codebase and no unchecked arithmetic is being performed, reduce the Severity of SWC-101 (overflow/underflow) findings. For all other classifications — reentrancy, tx.origin, timestamps, unchecked calls — treat Critical as the maximum possible value and investigate each case before escalating.03 — STACK CLAUDE WITH OTHER TOOLS.Claude may highlight intent-related issues which rule-based tools do not focus on due to their design limitations — for example, Claude identified a potential reentrancy issue in  where the benchmark did not label the issue. Both Slither and Mythril identify Data Flow and Control Flow issues at scale. Additionally, Human Experts evaluate flash loan risks, MEV (Maximal Extractable Value) risks, and Cross Contract Invariant Risks when evaluating complex protocols that manage real user funds. Therefore, utilize Claude as one layer along with Slither & Mythril as your two other layers when auditing contracts that contain real user funds.Durieux T. et al., Empirical review of automated analysis tools on 47,587 Ethereum smart contracts, ICSE 2020. Wei Z. et al., LLM-SmartAudit: Advanced smart contract vulnerability detection, IEEE Trans. Softw. Eng. 2024. Mehar M.I. et al., Understanding a revolutionary and flawed grand experiment in blockchain: The DAO attack, J. Cases Inf. Technol. 2019.

:::tip
The first article in a three-part series.Part 1 - where an LLM loses cross-service context and why local specs are not enough.Part 2 - archspec: a versioned architecture contract for services.Part 3 - archspec: feature investigation, contract updates, and implementation.I work at a large product company with thousands of microservices. In a system like that, even a small feature often crosses several services, events, and internal contracts. Some teams already use spec-driven development with LLMs to plan and review features, so I wanted to understand where this approach helps and where it starts to fail.As long as the task stays inside one service, things usually move quickly. The spec is short, and the description plus implementation fit into the model's context window. The trouble starts when a feature crosses several services. Each individual piece can look fine: clean layering, naming that follows the code style, tests passing, review comments resolved. But the system still behaves incorrectly. Typical failures include missing idempotency, skipped edge cases, and cyclic service calls. The more changes you ask the model to make, the more mistakes it tends to introduce.For the experiment, I built a separate Go project: a freelance marketplace. It contains 12 microservices connected through gRPC and a message broker. In this project, the broker is NATS. Some services store tasks and freelancer profiles. Others select candidates, calculate distances, verify portfolios, and send notifications. The project is deliberately designed around six categories of architectural traps. These traps do not show up inside a single service. They appear at service boundaries.The feature I used for the experiment was this: if the selected freelancer rejects an offer, the platform must automatically find the next suitable candidate, send that candidate a new offer, and notify the client about the reassignment.Claude wrote the spec, the implementation, and the unit tests, but the full rejection and reassignment scenario did not work end to end. Two independent reviews found the same class of bugs: every service looked fine in isolation, but the services did not work together correctly.You could say this needs an end-to-end test for the whole scenario, and that would be correct. But it still would not solve the whole problem. End-to-end tests are not always available, they are expensive to maintain, and they rarely cover rare edge cases, duplicate events, races, and unusual state combinations. The real failure happens earlier, while the model is still turning requirements into a plan. That is when it should collect the important constraints and context, and that is where it often misses them.A developer may know these rules, but not connect them to the feature at the right moment. For example, they may know that one service uses the Outbox, another deduplicates notifications, and a third expects data in a specific format. The problem is that these rules live in different places. The LLM can read the service docs, ask clarification questions, and still miss the link between them.The result is a detailed but incomplete spec: it describes local changes service by service, but misses the system invariants between them. The implementation may be neatly split into layers and pass component tests, while the bug only appears in the full scenario or during review.The setup is simple: twelve Go microservices, gRPC for synchronous calls, and a message broker for asynchronous events. Each service follows the same Clean Architecture layout: , , , , , and .  and  use the Transactional Outbox pattern so state changes and events are written together.In short:  receives client requests and proxies them to gRPC.  stores tasks and publishes  through the Outbox.  orchestrates matching: it calls , then , then , ranks candidates, and publishes . The closed services, , , and , are isolated by a NetworkPolicy, so they cannot be called directly. The only allowed entry point is .  listens to  and sends notifications, and  calculates distances.The project contains six architectural traps. They are normal microservice constraints, but an LLM can easily miss them when it reads services one by one.Closed services cannot be called directly., , and  are available only through ; this is enforced by a NetworkPolicy, a rule that limits network access to services. If an LLM calls those services directly, the code may look fine, but it violates the architecture boundary. has only one RPC. Its proto exposes only . If the feature description mentions skills or urgency, an LLM may assume methods such as  or  exist, but they do not.City data is already present in the freelancer profile. returns , , and .  is not needed for that data. It is needed for distance calculation by .The review author name is already stored in. A review has an  field, so  must not call back through  to fetch the author's name. Otherwise it is easy to create a review -> worker-facade -> review call chain.Bulk reads must use batch methods. The project already has  and . Without those, candidate matching turns into an N+1 problem: one request per candidate instead of one batch request.State and events must be written together. This is handled through the Outbox, for example  and . Consumers also deduplicate events by storing processed keys and dropping repeats. If state changes and events are saved separately, one step can succeed and the other can fail.The experiment task was called . The idea is simple: the client has already received a suitable freelancer, but that freelancer rejects the offer. At that moment, the platform should not send the task to manual handling. It should select the next candidate and send a new offer automatically.:::tip
freelancer rejection starts a new matching attempt;candidates with higher ratings go first; if ratings are equal, the closer candidate wins;the client receives a reassignment notification;after three failed reassignments, the task moves to .These requirements hide the important parts: where the closed-service boundary is, which key is used for notification deduplication, what city format must cross service boundaries, when a batch request is required, and which service must atomically write state together with an event.Those details decide whether the feature works.4. How I ran the experimentEach service has its own . It describes what the service owns, which RPCs it exposes, which events it publishes or consumes, and which other services it can call. There is also a project-level  with the full service list and links to architecture docs. Before implementation, Claude Code was expected to read those files and build a picture of the project.For planning, I used the superpowers:brainstorming skill on Sonnet 4.6. I gave Claude a prompt with the feature description. Claude asked two clarification questions and proposed three implementation approaches. I chose the event-driven approach, and Claude then prepared a complete spec.:::tip
How the brainstorming session actually wentOnly after that did I run two independent reviews: Claude Opus in a separate session, and Codex checked against the reference solution and project checklist. Both reviews showed the same thing: the full rejection and reassignment scenario did not behave as required.5. Cross-service bugs in the implementationClaude attached this sequence diagram to the plan:The diagram includes important pieces: Outbox, idempotency, and distance calculation so the system can pick the closest candidate when ratings are equal. If you read only the plan, especially without running the whole scenario, it looks reasonable. The problems start lower down, in the implementation.5.1. Idempotency key collisiondeduplicates events by . If an event with the same key has already arrived, the service drops it. That means every new offer needs its own : the first offer and every reassignment are different events for the consumer.In Claude's implementation, every reassignment receives the same . The model stores one  record and republishes it after every rejection instead of creating a new key for the new attempt.func (uc *NotificationUseCase) HandleMatchFound(event domain.MatchFoundEvent) {
    dedupKey := event.MatchID
    if dedupKey == "" {
        dedupKey = event.TaskID
    }

    if !uc.dedup.MarkProcessed(dedupKey) {
        log.Printf("duplicate match.found for %s, skipping", dedupKey)
        return
    }

    log.Printf("[STUB] client notified: task %s reassigned to worker %s", event.TaskID, event.WorkerID)
}
The first notification is sent. The next reassignments are dropped as duplicates. For the system, this is critical: a new offer has been created, but the event consumer does not process it.Local tests do not expose this.  correctly drops duplicates, and  correctly publishes a match-found event. The bug appears only in the connection between them: different offer attempts must not use the same idempotency key.This is easy to miss in review because the rule "one  per offer attempt" is written neither in the sender nor in the consumer. It belongs to their interaction, not to either service alone.5.2. A new write path without the OutboxThe project has a rule: when a service changes state and needs to publish an event, it must save both through the Outbox. For example,  does this through  and .In Claude's implementation, publishes directly to the message broker. After that,  receives the event and writes the rejection to  through a separate call.func (h *GatewayGRPCHandler) DeclineOffer(ctx context.Context, req *gatewayv1.DeclineOfferRequest) (*gatewayv1.DeclineOfferResponse, error) {
    if req.GetTaskId() == "" || req.GetWorkerId() == "" {
        return nil, status.Error(codes.InvalidArgument, "task_id and worker_id are required")
    }
    if h.nc == nil {
        return nil, status.Error(codes.Unavailable, "messaging unavailable")
    }
    payload, err := json.Marshal(offerDeclinedPayload{TaskID: req.GetTaskId(), WorkerID: req.GetWorkerId()})
    if err != nil {
        return nil, status.Errorf(codes.Internal, "marshal: %v", err)
    }
    if err := h.nc.Publish(natsSubjectOfferDeclined, payload); err != nil {
        return nil, status.Errorf(codes.Internal, "publish: %v", err)
    }
    return &gatewayv1.DeclineOfferResponse{Success: true}, nil
}
The problem is that the event and the state change are no longer atomic. The event can reach the message broker while the rejection is never recorded in . Or a duplicate event can be processed as a new rejection.At first glance, this looks fine: the gateway accepted a request, published an event, and  handled it. But this operation needs a shared contract. Rejecting an offer changes task state, so the rejection event must come from the Outbox of the service that owns task state.5.3. N+1 reads for ratingsRanking requires ratings for all candidates. In Claude's implementation, calls inside a loop. That means one network request to  for every candidate.candidates := make([]candidateEntry, 0, len(workers))
for _, w := range workers {
    rating, err := uc.ratings.GetAverageRating(ctx, w.ID)
    if err != nil {
        log.Printf("failed to get rating for worker %s: %v", w.ID, err)
        continue
    }
    candidates = append(candidates, candidateEntry{
        workerID:   w.ID,
        name:       w.Name,
        cityID:     w.CityID,
        rating:     rating,
        distanceKm: math.Inf(1),
    })
}
With twenty candidates, the service makes twenty network calls for ratings. The better design is to add a batch method and fetch all ratings in one request.This code still compiles, and it does not violate the current proto because only has for a single freelancer. The missing part is a design check: whenever one service calls another service inside a loop, the spec should ask whether that call needs a batch API. This rule was not written down.5.4. Lost state transitionIf candidates run out before the limit of three reassignments, the task must move to the final  state. In Claude's implementation, only logs and returns. It does not change task state.if int(count) >= len(result.Candidates) {
    log.Printf("ProcessOfferDeclined: candidates exhausted for task %s (count=%d, candidates=%d)", taskID, count, len(result.Candidates))
    return
}
As a result, the task can stay  or  even when there is no one left to offer it to. No  event is published either, so the client is not notified.The important rule is that this kind of dead end must change task state, not only write a log line. The requirements mentioned the limit of three reassignments, but they did not spell out what should happen if candidates run out earlier. The model did not fill in that gap.5.5. Two more bugs, brieflyDistance calculation needs city identifiers. In , the task has a  field that stores a display name such as . But  works with pairs of city identifiers.In Claude's implementation, sends a pair made from the freelancer's  and the task's  string:pairs := make([][2]string, len(candidates))
for i, c := range candidates {
    pairs[i] = [2]string{c.cityID, city}
}
That puts two formats into one request, for example  and .  cannot calculate the distance correctly, so the system can pick the wrong candidate.This is not a bug in one field or one method. The contract should explicitly say which city representation crosses the boundary between , , and : display name or .During brainstorming, Claude asked what the external call for rejecting an offer should look like. I answered: . The freelancer should be taken from the auth token on the server, not from the client request.The implementation ended up with DeclineOffer(taskId, workerId), which accepts  from the client. That means a client can pass someone else's  and reject an offer on behalf of another freelancer.My clarification was supposed to close exactly that risk, but it disappeared from the final implementation.The problem is not that Claude failed to read the files. It read the per-service  files, asked clarification questions, and wrote a detailed spec. But those documents mostly described each service in isolation, not the rules that connect several services.:::tip
These rules were not recorded explicitly:a new offer must receive a new , otherwise the event consumer thinks it has already processed that offer;an operation that changes task state and emits an event must go through the Outbox;if a service calls another service in a loop, the design must check whether a batch API is needed;if the scenario cannot continue, the task must move to a final status instead of just writing a log line;the contract must specify the city format: display name or .End-to-end tests help catch some of these bugs, but usually after implementation. I wanted to move the check earlier, to the moment when the LLM collects requirements and proposes a plan. For that, Markdown service descriptions are not enough. The model needs a structured contract: call graphs, endpoint contracts, idempotency keys, Outbox rules, batch calls, and state transitions.This contract can be checked on commit, reviewed in a pull request, and passed to an LLM before implementation. Free-form Markdown is too loose for that. It gets stale, its diffs are hard to review, and it does not force anyone to write down the rules between services.My conclusion is that another free-form Markdown file is not enough. Each service needs a machine-readable contract. That contract should contain not only endpoints and dependencies, but also the rules that usually get lost between services: idempotency keys, Outbox usage, batch calls, state transitions, and boundary data formats.In part two, I will show . It walks through all twelve services, extracts endpoints, dependencies, and message broker topics from the code, and then builds a YAML architecture contract for each service. From that spec, archspec generates C1/C2 and sequence diagrams that developers can read and review in a pull request together with the architecture contract diff.In part three, I will return to Smart Task Reassignment, the feature that automatically reassigns a task after a freelancer rejects an offer, through . The tool reads the affected service contracts before implementation, proposes changes to the architecture spec, and produces a plan that includes the rules between those services.Both tools are open source: is already available as a plugin. If you find a bug, an awkward workflow, or a missing rule, please open an issue in the repository.You can also discuss this with me on LinkedIn or X.

