NPOI is the most-downloaded free Excel library for .NET. The NuGet package has over 100 million downloads, it appears in countless Stack Overflow answers, and it powers Excel generation in thousands of production applications. It is also, by a wide margin, the least-documented popular library in the .NET ecosystem. The official documentation is a GitHub README with a few code snippets. There is no API reference site, no getting-started guide, no tutorial series.// NPOI: Create a workbook and write one cell
using NPOI.XSSF.UserModel;
using System.IO;

var workbook = new XSSFWorkbook();

var sheet = workbook.CreateSheet("Sheet1");

var row = sheet.CreateRow(0);

var cell = row.CreateCell(0);

cell.SetCellValue("Hello, Excel");

using var stream = new FileStream("hello.xlsx", FileMode.Create);

workbook.Write(stream);
// IronXL: Same result
var wb = IronXL.WorkBook.Create();

wb.DefaultWorkSheet["A1"].Value = "Hello, Excel";

wb.SaveAs("hello.xlsx");
Full disclosure: we are the engineering team behind IronXL, one of the libraries compared in this article. We use IronXL as the primary comparison because we know its architecture best, but we cover NPOI thoroughly and honestly, including the scenarios where its free license and open-source model make it the right choice.We have worked with teams that chose NPOI because it was free, teams that chose it because they came from Java and recognized the Apache POI patterns, and teams that chose it simply because it was the first result on NuGet. In all cases, the same questions come up: why is the API so verbose? Why do I need to create a row before I can create a cell? Where is the documentation? This article answers those questions, covers NPOI thoroughly enough to serve as the guide its maintainers never wrote, and provides a concrete comparison with IronXL for the scenarios where a more modern API or broader feature set justifies the cost.NPOI is a .NET port of Apache POI, the Java library for reading and writing Microsoft Office file formats. Apache POI was created in 2001 as part of the Apache Jakarta project, and it has been the standard way to manipulate Excel files in the Java ecosystem for over two decades. The name "POI" stands for "Poor Obfuscation Implementation", a reference to the difficulty of reverse-engineering Microsoft's binary file formats in the early 2000s.The .NET port was originally created by Tony Qu around 2008 under the name NPOI (the "N" for .NET). It faithfully replicated Apache POI's class hierarchy, naming conventions, and architectural patterns in C#. This means NPOI's API design reflects Java conventions, not .NET conventions, a distinction that becomes immediately apparent when you write your first NPOI code.The library is currently maintained by the nissl-lab organization on GitHub under the Apache 2.0 license. There is also an archived fork at dotnetcore/npoi that was part of the .NET Core Community organization, this fork is no longer maintained and should not be used for new projects, though it still appears in search results and can confuse developers evaluating the library.Like IronXL, NPOI is a pure .NET library that reads and writes Excel files entirely in-process. It does not depend on Microsoft Office, does not spawn external processes, and does not use COM Interop. This is NPOI's most important architectural advantage over Microsoft.Office.Interop.Excel, and it is the same advantage that IronXL, EPPlus, and ClosedXML share.NPOI implements its own parsers for two Excel file formats: (Horrible Spreadsheet Format): reads and writes the legacy .xls format (BIFF8, the binary format used by Excel 97-2003) (XML Spreadsheet Format): reads and writes the modern .xlsx format (OOXML, the XML-based format introduced in Excel 2007)These names come directly from Apache POI. Yes, "Horrible Spreadsheet Format" is the actual name, it reflects the Apache developers' frustration with Microsoft's proprietary binary format. The names are memorable, if nothing else.The NuGet package (NPOI version 2.8.x) includes both HSSF and XSSF support, plus HWPF/XWPF for Word documents and HSLF/XSLF for PowerPoint. For Excel-only projects, you install the same top-level package, there is no lightweight Excel-only variant.How Do You Set Up and Use NPOI?using NPOI.XSSF.UserModel;
using NPOI.SS.UserModel;
using System.IO;

XSSFWorkbook workbook = new XSSFWorkbook();

ISheet sheet = workbook.CreateSheet("Sales Report");

// Create header row
IRow headerRow = sheet.CreateRow(0);

headerRow.CreateCell(0).SetCellValue("Product");
headerRow.CreateCell(1).SetCellValue("Revenue");
headerRow.CreateCell(2).SetCellValue("Units");

// Create data rows
IRow dataRow1 = sheet.CreateRow(1);

dataRow1.CreateCell(0).SetCellValue("Widget A");
dataRow1.CreateCell(1).SetCellValue(15000.50);
dataRow1.CreateCell(2).SetCellValue(342);

IRow dataRow2 = sheet.CreateRow(2);

dataRow2.CreateCell(0).SetCellValue("Widget B");
dataRow2.CreateCell(1).SetCellValue(8200.75);
dataRow2.CreateCell(2).SetCellValue(198);

// Format header row
ICellStyle headerStyle = workbook.CreateCellStyle();

IFont headerFont = workbook.CreateFont();
headerFont.IsBold = true;
headerStyle.SetFont(headerFont);

for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++)
{
    headerRow.GetCell(i).CellStyle = headerStyle;
}

// Format currency column
IDataFormat format = workbook.CreateDataFormat();

ICellStyle currencyStyle = workbook.CreateCellStyle();
currencyStyle.DataFormat = format.GetFormat("$#,##0.00");

dataRow1.GetCell(1).CellStyle = currencyStyle;
dataRow2.GetCell(1).CellStyle = currencyStyle;

// Save
using FileStream stream = new FileStream("sales_report.xlsx", FileMode.Create);
workbook.Write(stream);
Notice several things about this code. You must explicitly create every row before you can create cells in it, there is no way to address a cell directly by coordinates or A1 notation. CreateRow(0) returns an IRow, and only then can you call CreateCell(0) on that row. This is the Java object model from Apache POI, translated directly to C#.The style system is also verbose by design. To make headers bold, you create an ICellStyle, create a separate IFont, set the font's IsBold property, attach the font to the style, and apply the style to each cell individually. This mirrors how Apache POI works in Java, functional, but requiring more ceremony than most .NET developers expect.The FileStream pattern for saving is important: NPOI's Write() method takes a Stream, not a file path. You must create the FileStream yourself and manage its lifecycle. In .NET 8, the using declaration simplifies this, but older code often has explicit try/finally blocks for stream disposal.using NPOI.SS.UserModel;
using System.IO;

IWorkbook workbook;

using (FileStream stream = new FileStream("inventory.xlsx", FileMode.Open, FileAccess.Read))
{
    workbook = WorkbookFactory.Create(stream);
}

ISheet sheet = workbook.GetSheetAt(0);

for (int rowIndex = 0; rowIndex <= sheet.LastRowNum; rowIndex++)
{
    IRow row = sheet.GetRow(rowIndex);
    if (row == null) continue;

    for (int colIndex = 0; colIndex < row.LastCellNum; colIndex++)
    {
        ICell cell = row.GetCell(colIndex);
        if (cell == null) continue;

        switch (cell.CellType)
        {
            case CellType.String:
                Console.Write(cell.StringCellValue);
                break;

            case CellType.Numeric:
                Console.Write(cell.NumericCellValue);
                break;

            case CellType.Boolean:
                Console.Write(cell.BooleanCellValue);
                break;

            default:
                Console.Write(cell.ToString());
                break;
        }
        Console.Write("\t");
    }
    Console.WriteLine();
}
Reading an Excel File with NPOIThe WorkbookFactory.Create() method auto-detects whether the file is XLS or XLSX and returns the appropriate IWorkbook implementation. This is the recommended way to open files when you do not know the format in advance.The cell type switch is required because NPOI does not provide typed accessors that handle conversion automatically. If you call StringCellValue on a numeric cell, you get an exception, not a string representation of the number. You must check CellType first and branch accordingly. This is another pattern inherited from Apache POI's Java API.Null checks for rows and cells are critical. Unlike Excel itself (where every cell in the used range "exists"), NPOI returns null for rows that were never created and for cells within a row that were never written. Forgetting these null checks is the most common NPOI bug we see in production code.IRow totalRow = sheet.CreateRow(3);

totalRow.CreateCell(0).SetCellValue("Total");

ICell formulaCell = totalRow.CreateCell(1);

formulaCell.SetCellFormula("SUM(B2:B3)");

ICell avgCell = totalRow.CreateCell(2);

avgCell.SetCellFormula("AVERAGE(C2:C3)");
NPOI passes formulas as strings, similar to other Excel libraries. Note the method is SetCellFormula() (without the leading = sign), including the = is a common mistake that produces an invalid formula. NPOI writes the formula to the file but does not evaluate it by default. When the file is opened in Excel, Excel recalculates the formulas. If you need evaluated values before the file is opened, you can call XSSFFormulaEvaluator.EvaluateAllFormulaCells(workbook), but the built-in evaluator supports a smaller set of functions than Excel's native engine.What Is the HSSF/XSSF Dual API You Must Understand?This is the aspect of NPOI that trips up the most developers, and it is almost never explained in existing tutorials. NPOI has two completely separate implementations for XLS and XLSX files, and choosing the wrong one produces runtime errors, not compile-time errors.|    |  |  |
|----|----|----|
|  | NPOI.HSSF.UserModel | NPOI.XSSF.UserModel |
|  | HSSFWorkbook | XSSFWorkbook |
|  | BIFF8 (binary, 1997) | OOXML (XML-based, 2007) |
|  | 65,536 | 1,048,576 |
|  | 256 | 16,384 |
|  | Compact (binary) | Larger (XML + ZIP) |
|  | Lower | Higher (full DOM in memory) |If you create an HSSFWorkbook and try to save it as .xlsx, or create an XSSFWorkbook and save as .xls, the resulting file will be corrupt. There is no automatic format conversion.NPOI provides a set of interfaces — IWorkbook, ISheet, IRow, ICell, ICellStyle — that abstract over both implementations. Code written against these interfaces works with either format:using NPOI.SS.UserModel;

IWorkbook CreateWorkbook(string format)
{
    return format switch
    {
        ".xls" => new NPOI.HSSF.UserModel.HSSFWorkbook(),
        ".xlsx" => new NPOI.XSSF.UserModel.XSSFWorkbook(),
        _ => throw new ArgumentException($"Unsupported format: {format}")
    };
}
A pragmatic approach is to always use the IWorkbook/ISheet/IRow/ICell interfaces in your business logic, and only reference the concrete HSSFWorkbook or XSSFWorkbook classes at the point of creation. This keeps your code format-agnostic and makes it easy to switch between XLS and XLSX output.WorkbookFactory: The Recommended Entry Pointusing FileStream fs = new FileStream(filePath, FileMode.Open, FileAccess.Read);

IWorkbook workbook = WorkbookFactory.Create(fs);
For write operations, you must choose the correct concrete class upfront. There is no WorkbookFactory.Create() overload that takes a desired output format.Where Does NPOI Fall Short?NPOI is a working library that has served the .NET community for over 15 years. We are not going to pretend it is broken, it is not. But it has real limitations that affect developer productivity, and understanding them before you commit to NPOI for a new project can save significant time.This is NPOI's most significant limitation. The official GitHub repository has a README with a feature list and a handful of code snippets. The npoi-tutorial repository has bare code samples with no explanatory text. There is no API reference website, no searchable documentation, and no tutorial series.In production systems, this means your developers will learn NPOI from Stack Overflow answers (many of which are 5-10 years old and target .NET Framework), from the Apache POI Java documentation (which requires mental translation to C#), or from trial and error. The hidden cost of "free" software is often the time your team spends figuring out how to use it.Verbose API Inherited from JavaNPOI's API is a faithful translation of Apache POI's Java API. This means it follows Java conventions, not .NET conventions:// NPOI: Write a value to cell B2
IRow row = sheet.CreateRow(1);

ICell cell = row.CreateCell(1);

cell.SetCellValue("Hello");

// IronXL: Same operation
sheet["B2"].Value = "Hello";
The difference is not just syntactic. In NPOI, you must know that row index 1 and column index 1 correspond to cell B2. There is no A1-notation addressing. You must create the row before you can create cells in it. And if the row already exists (because you already called CreateRow(1) earlier), calling CreateRow(1) again overwrites it, silently destroying any cells you already created.No LINQ or Range OperationsIronXL treats cell ranges as IEnumerable collections, which means you can use LINQ queries on them:// IronXL: Sum all revenue values above 10,000
decimal highRevenue = sheet["B2:B100"]
    .Where(cell => cell.DecimalValue > 10000)
    .Sum(cell => cell.DecimalValue);
NPOI has no equivalent. To achieve the same result, you must write an explicit loop:// NPOI: Same operation
double highRevenue = 0;

for (int i = 1; i <= sheet.LastRowNum; i++)
{
    IRow row = sheet.GetRow(i);
    if (row == null) continue;

    ICell cell = row.GetCell(1);

    if (cell == null || cell.CellType != CellType.Numeric) continue;

    if (cell.NumericCellValue > 10000)
        highRevenue += cell.NumericCellValue;
}
The NPOI version is 9 lines. The IronXL version is 3. More importantly, the IronXL version composes with the rest of the LINQ ecosystem, you can chain .GroupBy(), .OrderBy(), .Select(), and any other LINQ operator.NPOI reads and writes XLS and XLSX files. That is the extent of its format support. If your pipeline needs to import CSV data, convert JSON to Excel, or export a workbook as XML, NPOI cannot help, you need a separate library (like CsvHelper or System.Text.Json) to handle the format conversion, then populate NPOI cells manually.IronXL supports CSV, JSON, XML, and TSV as native import/export formats, WorkBook.Load("data.csv") reads a CSV directly into a workbook, and workbook.SaveAs("output.json") exports to JSON.NPOI includes a formula evaluator (XSSFFormulaEvaluator / HSSFFormulaEvaluator) that can evaluate formulas without opening the file in Excel. However, the evaluator supports a smaller set of functions than Excel's native engine or IronXL's 450+ function library. Common functions like SUM, AVERAGE, IF, and VLOOKUP work correctly, but more advanced functions may return errors or incorrect results.Memory Usage with Large FilesXSSF (the XLSX implementation) loads the entire SpreadsheetML XML document into an in-memory DOM tree. For large workbooks (50,000+ rows), this can consume significant memory — often 5-10x the file size on disk. Apache POI addressed this in Java with the SXSSF (Streaming XSSF) implementation, and NPOI includes a port of this streaming API, but it is write-only (you cannot read existing large files with it) and has limited formatting support.IronXL is a .NET library that reads and writes Excel files entirely in-process, without any dependency on Microsoft Office — the same deployment model as NPOI. The fundamental difference is not in what the libraries do, but in how they were built. NPOI is a port of a Java library. IronXL was designed from scratch as a .NET library, which means its API follows .NET conventions: properties instead of getter/setter methods, LINQ-compatible collections, typed cell accessors, and fluent method chaining.|  |  |  |
|----|----|----|
|  | Port of Apache POI (Java) | Native .NET library |
|  | Java-ported (verbose, explicit) | .NET-native (fluent, concise) |
|  | Row/column indices only | sheet["A1"] + sheet[row, col] |
|  | No | Yes (ranges are IEnumerable) |
|  | None | None |
|  | .NET Framework, .NET Core, .NET 8 | .NET Framework, .NET Core, .NET 8+ |
|  | Yes (HSSF) | Yes (native BIFF parser) |
|  | Yes (XSSF) | Yes (native OOXML parser) |
|  | No | Native support |
|  | Limited evaluator | 450+ functions |
|  | GitHub README only | Comprehensive docs + tutorials |
|  | Apache 2.0 (free) | Perpetual $999 (1 dev) |
|  | GitHub issues (community) | Dedicated engineering support |dotnet add package IronXL.Excel
No additional software required. The package works on Windows, Linux, and macOS, and runs in Docker containers, Azure App Service, AWS Lambda, and CI/CD pipelines without modification.IronXL's API is designed for .NET developers who expect .NET conventions:using IronXL;

WorkBook workbook = WorkBook.Load("inventory.xlsx");

WorkSheet sheet = workbook.DefaultWorkSheet;

// A1-notation cell access
string productName = sheet["A2"].StringValue;

double revenue = sheet["B2"].DoubleValue;

// Range operations with LINQ
decimal totalRevenue = sheet["B2:B100"].DecimalValue.Sum();

// Typed aggregation
int maxUnits = (int)sheet["C2:C100"].Max();
Every cell access returns a typed value. Range selections return LINQ-compatible collections. There is no need to check CellType, no null-checking for rows that might not exist, and no manual row/cell creation ceremony. The API reflects how .NET developers expect to work with data collections.IronXL uses a perpetual license model: $999 for a single developer (Lite), $1,199 for 3 developers (Plus), $2,399 for 10 developers (Professional). One-time purchase includes 1 year of updates and support. The 30-day free trial is fully functional with no limitations.The tradeoff you are making here is explicit: NPOI costs $0 forever. IronXL costs money but provides comprehensive documentation, a modern API, broader format support, and dedicated support. For a team of 3 developers spending 2 days learning NPOI's undocumented API patterns, the "free" library already cost $2,000+ in developer time — more than IronXL's Plus license.The most useful comparison is code, not marketing. Below we show five common Excel operations implemented in both NPOI and IronXL, with line counts and architectural explanations for each difference.Create a Workbook, Add Data, and Save// NPOI
using NPOI.XSSF.UserModel;
using System.IO;

XSSFWorkbook workbook = new XSSFWorkbook();

ISheet sheet = workbook.CreateSheet("Quarterly Report");

IRow header = sheet.CreateRow(0);

header.CreateCell(0).SetCellValue("Quarter");
header.CreateCell(1).SetCellValue("Revenue");
header.CreateCell(2).SetCellValue("Expenses");

IRow q1 = sheet.CreateRow(1);

q1.CreateCell(0).SetCellValue("Q1 2026");
q1.CreateCell(1).SetCellValue(245000);
q1.CreateCell(2).SetCellValue(182000);

IRow q2 = sheet.CreateRow(2);

q2.CreateCell(0).SetCellValue("Q2 2026");
q2.CreateCell(1).SetCellValue(312000);
q2.CreateCell(2).SetCellValue(198000);

using FileStream stream = new FileStream("quarterly.xlsx", FileMode.Create);

workbook.Write(stream);
// IronXL
using IronXL;

WorkBook workbook = WorkBook.Create();

WorkSheet sheet = workbook.CreateWorkSheet("Quarterly Report");

sheet["A1"].Value = "Quarter";
sheet["B1"].Value = "Revenue";
sheet["C1"].Value = "Expenses";

sheet["A2"].Value = "Q1 2026";
sheet["B2"].Value = 245000;
sheet["C2"].Value = 182000;

sheet["A3"].Value = "Q2 2026";
sheet["B3"].Value = 312000;
sheet["C3"].Value = 198000;

workbook.SaveAs("quarterly.xlsx");
NPOI: 19 lines. IronXL: 15 lines. The primary difference is the row/cell creation model. NPOI requires CreateRow() then CreateCell() for every cell, you address cells by numeric indices (row 0, column 0). IronXL uses A1-notation (sheet["A1"]) and creates underlying structures automatically. For small workbooks the difference is cosmetic, but it compounds in larger codebases.Read an Existing File and Extract Data// NPOI
using NPOI.SS.UserModel;
using System.IO;
using System.Collections.Generic;

List<Dictionary<string, object>> records = new();

using (FileStream stream = new FileStream("sales.xlsx", FileMode.Open, FileAccess.Read))
{
    IWorkbook workbook = WorkbookFactory.Create(stream);
    ISheet sheet = workbook.GetSheetAt(0);
    IRow headerRow = sheet.GetRow(0);

    for (int i = 1; i <= sheet.LastRowNum; i++)
    {
        IRow row = sheet.GetRow(i);

        if (row == null) continue;
        var record = new Dictionary<string, object>();

        for (int j = 0; j < headerRow.LastCellNum; j++)
        {
            string key = headerRow.GetCell(j)?.StringCellValue ?? $"Column{j}";
            ICell cell = row.GetCell(j);
            record[key] = cell?.CellType switch
            {
                CellType.Numeric => cell.NumericCellValue,
                CellType.String => cell.StringCellValue,
                CellType.Boolean => cell.BooleanCellValue,
                _ => cell?.ToString() ?? ""
            };
        }
        records.Add(record);
    }
}
// IronXL
using IronXL;
using System.Linq;

WorkBook workbook = WorkBook.Load("sales.xlsx");
WorkSheet sheet = workbook.DefaultWorkSheet;

var records = sheet.Rows
    .Skip(1)
    .Select(row => new
    {
        Product = row.Columns[0].StringValue,
        Revenue = row.Columns[1].DoubleValue,
        Units = row.Columns[2].IntValue
    })
    .ToList();
NPOI: 25 lines. IronXL: 13 lines. The critical difference here is type safety. NPOI forces you to check CellType before accessing a value, calling StringCellValue on a numeric cell throws an exception. IronXL provides typed accessors (StringValue, DoubleValue, IntValue) that handle conversions internally. The null-checking burden in NPOI (rows and cells can both be null) disappears entirely in IronXL.// NPOI
ICellStyle currencyStyle = workbook.CreateCellStyle();
IDataFormat dataFormat = workbook.CreateDataFormat();
currencyStyle.DataFormat = dataFormat.GetFormat("$#,##0.00");

ICellStyle headerStyle = workbook.CreateCellStyle();

IFont headerFont = workbook.CreateFont();

headerFont.IsBold = true;
headerFont.FontHeightInPoints = 12;
headerStyle.SetFont(headerFont);
headerStyle.FillForegroundColor = NPOI.HSSF.Util.HSSFColor.Grey25Percent.Index;
headerStyle.FillPattern = FillPattern.SolidForeground;
headerRow.GetCell(0).CellStyle = headerStyle;
headerRow.GetCell(1).CellStyle = headerStyle;

dataRow.GetCell(1).CellStyle = currencyStyle;
NPOI Styled Worksheet Output// IronXL
sheet["A1:C1"].Style.Font.Bold = true;
sheet["A1:C1"].Style.Font.Height = 12;
sheet["A1:C1"].Style.BackgroundColor = "#D9D9D9";
sheet["B2:B10"].FormatString = "$#,##0.00";
NPOI: 14 lines. IronXL: 4 lines. The NPOI style system requires you to create ICellStyle and IFont objects on the workbook, configure them, and apply them cell by cell. You cannot apply a style to a range, you must loop through cells. IronXL applies styles directly to ranges via a fluent property chain. The NPOI approach has one advantage: explicit style objects are reusable, which can matter if you are formatting thousands of cells (though IronXL handles this efficiently with its April 2026 performance update, 25-393x faster style application on large spreadsheets).// NPOI
IRow totalRow = sheet.CreateRow(sheet.LastRowNum + 1);
totalRow.CreateCell(0).SetCellValue("Total");
ICell sumCell = totalRow.CreateCell(1);

sumCell.SetCellFormula("SUM(B2:B10)");
ICell avgCell = totalRow.CreateCell(2);

avgCell.SetCellFormula("AVERAGE(C2:C10)");
XSSFFormulaEvaluator.EvaluateAllFormulaCells(workbook);

double total = sumCell.NumericCellValue;
// IronXL
sheet["A11"].Value = "Total";
sheet["B11"].Formula = "=SUM(B2:B10)";
sheet["C11"].Formula = "=AVERAGE(C2:C10)";
decimal total = sheet["B11"].DecimalValue;
NPOI: 9 lines. IronXL: 4 lines. Two differences stand out. First, NPOI's SetCellFormula() takes the formula without the leading = sign, while IronXL's Formula property includes it, matching Excel's own convention. Second, formula evaluation: NPOI requires an explicit call to XSSFFormulaEvaluator.EvaluateAllFormulaCells() before you can read computed values. IronXL evaluates formulas automatically when you access the cell's value. NPOI's built-in evaluator handles standard functions well but covers fewer of Excel's built-in function library than IronXL's 450+ function engine.Multi-Sheet Workbook Management// NPOI
XSSFWorkbook workbook = new XSSFWorkbook();

ISheet summary = workbook.CreateSheet("Summary");

ISheet details = workbook.CreateSheet("Details");

ISheet appendix = workbook.CreateSheet("Appendix");

// Copy data from one sheet to another (no built-in method)
// Must iterate rows and cells manually:
for (int i = 0; i <= details.LastRowNum; i++)
{
    IRow sourceRow = details.GetRow(i);
    if (sourceRow == null) continue;
    IRow targetRow = appendix.CreateRow(i);
    for (int j = 0; j < sourceRow.LastCellNum; j++)
    {
        ICell sourceCell = sourceRow.GetCell(j);
        if (sourceCell == null) continue;
        ICell targetCell = targetRow.CreateCell(j);

        switch (sourceCell.CellType)
        {
            case CellType.String:
                targetCell.SetCellValue(sourceCell.StringCellValue);
                break;

            case CellType.Numeric:
                targetCell.SetCellValue(sourceCell.NumericCellValue);
                break;

            case CellType.Boolean:
                targetCell.SetCellValue(sourceCell.BooleanCellValue);
                break;

            case CellType.Formula:
                targetCell.SetCellFormula(sourceCell.CellFormula);
                break;

        }
    }
}
// IronXL

WorkBook workbook = WorkBook.Create();

WorkSheet summary = workbook.CreateWorkSheet("Summary");

WorkSheet details = workbook.CreateWorkSheet("Details");

WorkSheet appendix = workbook.CreateWorkSheet("Appendix");

// Copy range from one sheet to another
details["A1:Z100"].Copy(appendix, "A1");
NPOI: 30 lines. IronXL: 6 lines. Sheet copying is where the API gap becomes most dramatic. NPOI has no built-in method to copy a range or sheet, you must iterate every row and cell, check types, and transfer values individually. Styles, merged cells, and conditional formatting require additional loops. IronXL provides a single Copy() method that handles values, formulas, styles, and formatting in one operation.DataTable Import and Export// NPOI: Export DataTable to Excel
using System.Data;

DataTable dt = GetSalesData(); // from your database

ISheet sheet = workbook.CreateSheet("Sales Data");

// Write headers
IRow headerRow = sheet.CreateRow(0);

for (int col = 0; col < dt.Columns.Count; col++)
{
    headerRow.CreateCell(col).SetCellValue(dt.Columns[col].ColumnName);
}

// Write data
for (int rowIndex = 0; rowIndex < dt.Rows.Count; rowIndex++)
{
    IRow dataRow = sheet.CreateRow(rowIndex + 1);

    for (int col = 0; col < dt.Columns.Count; col++)
    {
        ICell cell = dataRow.CreateCell(col);
        object value = dt.Rows[rowIndex][col];
        if (value is double d) cell.SetCellValue(d);
        else if (value is int i) cell.SetCellValue(i);
        else if (value is DateTime date) cell.SetCellValue(date);
        else cell.SetCellValue(value?.ToString() ?? "");
    }
}
NPOI DataTable to Excel Output// IronXL: Same operation
DataTable dt = GetSalesData();

WorkBook workbook = WorkBook.Create();

WorkSheet sheet = workbook.DefaultWorkSheet;

sheet.LoadFromDataTable(dt, true);

workbook.SaveAs("sales_export.xlsx");
NPOI: 22 lines. IronXL: 4 lines. NPOI has no built-in DataTable integration, you must iterate rows and columns, check types, and set values individually. IronXL's LoadFromDataTable() method handles headers, type detection, and cell population in one call. Going the other direction, IronXL can also export a worksheet to a DataTable with sheet.ToDataTable().Both NPOI and IronXL are in-process .NET libraries. Neither spawns an external process, and neither requires Microsoft Office, a significant advantage over Microsoft.Office.Interop.Excel, which we covered in depth in our companion article on Interop. Both libraries work in server environments, Docker containers, CI/CD pipelines, and cloud functions without additional dependencies.The memory comparison depends on the file format and workbook size:Small to medium workbooks (under 10,000 rows): Both libraries perform well. NPOI's XSSF implementation and IronXL's OOXML parser both load the file into memory; practical differences are negligible. (50,000+ rows): NPOI's XSSF builds a full XML DOM tree in memory, which can consume 5-10x the file size on disk. IronXL uses a more memory-efficient internal representation. For NPOI, the streaming writer (SXSSFWorkbook) can reduce write-side memory for large datasets, but it is write-only, there is no streaming reader.: NPOI's HSSF implementation is generally more memory-efficient than XSSF for the same data, because the binary format is more compact. However, the 65,536 row limit of XLS makes this relevant only for smaller datasets.In production systems where memory matters, profile both libraries with your actual workloads. Theoretical comparisons are less useful than measuring against your specific data shapes and volumes.|  |  |  |
